r a century are now in universal demand. Recounting the history of comics from the nineteenth-century rise of sequential comics to the newspaper strip, through comic books and underground comix, to the graphic novel and webcomics, Gardner shows why they offer the best models for rethinking storytelling in the twenty-first century. In the process, he reminds us of some beloved characters from our past and present, including Happy Hooligan, Krazy Kat, Crypt Keeper, and Mr. Natural.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aComic books, strips, etcxHistory and criticismxUnited States. 0aComic books, strips, etczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictures and comic booksxUnited States. 0aMotion pictures and comic bookszUnited States. 0aNarration (Rhetoric)xUnited States. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comics & Graphic Novels.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478178740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804781787423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804781787.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles